  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "buddhism-expert",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "No to line 17 note, one note at line 25 is sufficient",
    "content": "**No. One note at line 25 is sufficient.**\n\nAt line 17, the reader has not yet encountered 境 (Jing) as a technical term. Telling them \"境界 = boundary of Jing\" at this point gives them information they cannot yet use -- they do not know what Jing is. It would read as a cryptic forward-reference that creates confusion rather than illumination.\n\nLine 25 is where 境界 and bare 境 appear side by side. By this point the reader is in the preface of the essay titled \"范畴论与境\" -- they have seen 境 in the title and are about to encounter its formal definition. The note lands at the moment the reader is equipped to receive it.\n\nFront-loading the connection at line 17 also undermines the reading experience. The author's own text moves from ordinary 境界 to technical 境 gradually -- the reader should undergo the same transition. Spoiling it at line 17 is like explaining a joke before the punchline.\n\nOne note, line 25, doing both jobs (etymology + conceptual birth). Keep it clean.\n"
  }
}
